Model Building¶

For the model building the input and output both are images so we have to use a convolutional model, for this problem statement I have used the U-net convolutional Auto Encoder and the method is semantic segmentation, since its a domain application of an Auto Encoder and we just want to clip the desired values of the object to either 255 or 0, an Auto Encoder approach felt the right one for me, so the architecture used is taken from https://lmb.informatik.uni-freiburg.de/people/ronneber/u-net/

The first encoder part consists of encoding the sematic information into an encoded representation which is consisting of simultaneous convolutions followed by dropout followed by another convolution and then finally max pooling which is then the decoder which contains the same architecture which is decodes the encoded information into constructing the mask from the input image as a binary boolean value between 0-1. The kernels weights are initialised using he_normal distribution although glorot_normal can also be used here, since we need to preserve the dimensionality, the images are padded with same padding.

since the output consists of predicting a mask value between 0-1 we use a binary_crossentropy function and the choice of evalutation metrics used is accuracy

the optimiser used in this model is adam, its one of the most commonly used optimisers is proven to show state of the art results hence the choice.

In [8]:
inputs = tf.keras.layers.Input((IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH, IMG_CHANNELS))
s = tf.keras.layers.Lambda(lambda x: x / 255)(inputs)
c1 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(s)
c1 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(c1)
c1 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c1)
p1 = tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(c1)

c2 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(p1)
c2 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(c2)
c2 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c2)
p2 = tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(c2)
 
c3 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(p2)
c3 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(c3)
c3 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c3)
p3 = tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(c3)
 
c4 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(p3)
c4 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(c4)
c4 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c4)
p4 = tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2))(c4)
 
c5 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(p4)
c5 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3)(c5)
c5 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(256, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c5)

#Expansive path 
u6 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(128, (2, 2), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c5)
u6 = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([u6, c4])
c6 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(u6)
c6 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(c6)
c6 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c6)
 
u7 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(64, (2, 2), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c6)
u7 = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([u7, c3])
c7 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(u7)
c7 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2)(c7)
c7 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c7)
 
u8 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(32, (2, 2), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c7)
u8 = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([u8, c2])
c8 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(u8)
c8 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(c8)
c8 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c8)
 
u9 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2DTranspose(16, (2, 2), strides=(2, 2), padding='same')(c8)
u9 = tf.keras.layers.concatenate([u9, c1], axis=3)
c9 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(u9)
c9 = tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.1)(c9)
c9 = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(16, (3, 3), activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal', padding='same')(c9)
 
outputs = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(1, (1, 1), activation='sigmoid')(c9)
 
model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[inputs], outputs=[outputs])
model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

Callbacks¶

I have used the early stopping callback with a patience value of 5 to prevent the model from overfitting, which monitors the validation loss, and also a log for the model measurements

In [9]:
checkpointer=tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint('Model.h5',verbose=1, save_best_only=True)
callbacks=[tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=5, monitor='val_loss'), tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(log_dir='/content/logs')]

for n, id_ in tqdm(enumerate(train_ids), total=len(train_ids)):   
    path = '/content/DUTS-TR/train/DUTS-TR-Image/'
    img = imread(path + id_)[:,:,:IMG_CHANNELS]  
    img = resize(img, (IMG_HEIGHT, IMG_WIDTH), mode='constant', preserve_range=True)
    x_train[n] = img

Results¶

The model is performing quite well on training data and also well on test data as shown below from the examples

(since the masked image is a boolean value I have converted into a uint8 type) the images are thresholded using a 0.5 probability

In [20]:
preds_train = model.predict(x_train[:int(x_train.shape[0]*0.9)], verbose=1)
preds_val = model.predict(x_train[int(x_train.shape[0]*0.9):], verbose=1)
preds_test = model.predict(x_test, verbose=1)

preds_test_t = (preds_test > 0.5).astype(np.bool)



ix = random.randint(0, len(preds_train_t))

display=np.zeros((128,128),dtype=np.uint8)
image=y_train[ix][:,:,0]
for i in range(128):
  for j in range(128):
    if image[i][j]== False:
      display[i][j]=0
    else:
      display[i][j]=255

Please provide answers to the following questions in the NOTEBOOK as Markdown:

  1. Name the types of image segmentation or similar things you found on the internet and what made you choose the current approach?

The method I used is semantic segmentation and the model I've used is convolutional auto encoder model, I have used the U-net convolutional Auto Encoder, and since its a domain application of an Auto Encoder and we just want to clip the desired values of the object to either 255 or 0 and find the mask for the given image, another reason is I've worked with the auto encoder pipeline before hence this approach felt the right one for me

Did you try other approaches too? If yes, what were their results?

Yes, I did try semantic segmentation using XG Boost Regression but the accuracy was not up to what I had desired.

If you read other approaches/research papers/techniques, what is the difference?

I think if you compare the approaches semantic was right since multiple objects are taken into account in the mask as one entity and if we take instance segmentation, there were images where single mask consisted of an overlap of two objects.

between your approach and others? What are the main highlights about your approach that makes it better than others? It could be anything like your architecture, some connection, some layers, data pre-processing technique, some special loss function, unique training style and so on. The usage of an auto encoder approach, traditional methods consists of using a convolution neural network like resnet for feature extraction and object detection models like c3d and then later add a regression to predict the pixel values but, since the domain application of auto encoders is not used much and its one of the forlorn bunch of neural networks we can come across (for domain use cases) it was a unique method and as far as the the other training techniques i did trail and error for various things like the optimisers i did try adagrad but turned out adam worked like a charm, also i did try chaning the kernal initialisers to different distributions but best results were from he and glorot initialisers.

  1. What did you use as a baseline and what were the results? There are lots of metrics but why did you use what you have used? How did you improve further? Did you try anything to improve the existing results? If not, what could you have done?

I used a few models from the internet and i had already worked on Auto Encoder pipeline before so as soon as i saw the problem statement i knew that this would be the best course of approach although it took me to some tutorials on youtube and various other trail and error techniques to set it up.
